# LogicN v1 Formal Grammar (EBNF)

## Status

```text
Spec status: v1 canonical grammar
Implementation status: Phase 4 parser is partial; guarded flow, route, fn,
intent, compute target, and some expression forms remain Phase 7+ work.
```

This grammar defines the intended v1 surface syntax for the Canonical Example
Corpus. It is more complete than the current TypeScript prototype parser.

## Lexical Conventions

```ebnf
letter              = "A".."Z" | "a".."z" | "_" ;
digit               = "0".."9" ;
identifier          = letter , { letter | digit } ;
type_identifier     = "A".."Z" , { letter | digit } ;
enum_case           = type_identifier ;

integer_literal     = digit , { digit } ;
decimal_literal     = digit , { digit } , "." , digit , { digit } ;
string_literal      = '"' , { character | escape_sequence } , '"' ;
char_literal        = "'" , character , "'" ;
bool_literal        = "true" | "false" ;

literal             = decimal_literal
                    | integer_literal
                    | string_literal
                    | char_literal
                    | bool_literal ;

comment             = line_comment | doc_comment ;
line_comment        = "//" , { character } ;
doc_comment         = "///" , { character } ;
```

Whitespace and comments separate tokens and are otherwise insignificant except
where examples use newlines for readability.

## Compilation Unit

```ebnf
compilation_unit    = { top_level_item } ;

top_level_item      = type_decl
                    | record_decl
                    | enum_decl
                    | flow_decl
                    | route_decl
                    | import_decl ;

import_decl         = "import" , qualified_name , [ "as" , identifier ] ;
```

`fn` is intentionally absent from `top_level_item`; helper functions may only
appear inside a flow body.

## Types

```ebnf
type_decl           = "type" , type_identifier , ( type_alias | type_body ) ;
record_decl         = "record" , type_identifier , type_body ;

type_alias          = "=" , type_ref ;
type_body           = "{" , { field_decl } , "}" ;
field_decl          = identifier , ":" , type_ref ;

type_ref            = [ type_governance_qualifier ] , primary_type_ref ,
                      { type_state_qualifier } ;

type_governance_qualifier
                    = "protected" | "redacted" ;

primary_type_ref    = type_identifier , [ generic_args ]
                    | "Brand" , "<" , type_ref , "," , string_literal , ">"
                    | "(" , type_ref , ")" ;

generic_args        = "<" , type_ref , { "," , type_ref } , ">" ;

type_state_qualifier
                    = "unsafe" | "safe" | "validated" | "unvalidated"
                    | "secure" | "secret" ;
```

`protected` and `redacted` are prefix governance qualifiers. `String unsafe` is
a postfix value-state type annotation. `Email protected` and `Email redacted`
are invalid.

## Enums, Option, Result, and Match

```ebnf
enum_decl           = "enum" , type_identifier , "{" ,
                      [ enum_case_list ] , "}" ;

enum_case_list      = enum_case , { enum_separator , enum_case } ,
                      [ enum_separator ] ;
enum_separator      = "," | newline ;

match_expr          = "match" , expression , "{" , { match_arm } , "}" ;
match_arm           = pattern , "=>" , expression , [ "," ] ;

pattern             = "_"
                    | enum_case
                    | qualified_enum_case
                    | option_pattern
                    | result_pattern
                    | literal
                    | identifier ;

qualified_enum_case = type_identifier , "." , enum_case ;
option_pattern      = "Some" , "(" , pattern , ")" | "None" ;
result_pattern      = "Ok" , "(" , pattern , ")" | "Err" , "(" , pattern , ")" ;
```

`Option<T>` and `Result<T, E>` are standard generic types. Matches over enums,
`Option`, and `Result` must be exhaustive unless a wildcard arm is accepted by
policy. General exhaustiveness diagnostics use `LLN-MATCH-*`; type-level
match diagnostics may also report `LLN-TYPE-021`.

## Flow Declarations

```ebnf
flow_decl           = [ flow_qualifier ] , "flow" , identifier ,
                      "(" , [ param_list ] , ")" , "->" , type_ref ,
                      { flow_clause } , block ;

flow_qualifier      = "pure" | "guarded" | "secure" ;

param_list          = param , { "," , param } ;
param               = [ "readonly" ] , identifier , ":" , type_ref ;

flow_clause         = effects_clause
                    | intent_clause
                    | compute_target_block ;

effects_clause      = [ "with" ] , "effects" , "[" ,
                      [ effect_name , { "," , effect_name } ] , "]" ;

effect_name         = identifier , "." , identifier ,
                      { "." , identifier } ;

intent_clause       = "intent" , string_literal ;
```

Canonical v1 examples use `with effects [...]`; earlier examples and docs also
show `effects [...]`. The parser should accept both during migration and the
formatter should emit `with effects [...]` for guarded/secure flows.

Rules:

- `pure flow` must not declare or observe effects.
- `guarded flow` must declare every effect it uses, including effects used by
  local `fn` helpers.
- `secure flow` is the trust-boundary form and may declare effects, intent,
  governance, authority, and audit requirements.

## Local fn

```ebnf
fn_decl             = "fn" , identifier , "(" , [ param_list ] , ")" ,
                      "->" , type_ref , block ;
```

`fn_decl` is valid only as a `statement` inside a flow body. It cannot appear
at top level, cannot declare `effects`, cannot request authority, is always
synchronous, and cannot spawn tasks.

## Routes

```ebnf
route_decl          = "route" , route_method , string_literal , "{" ,
                      route_request ,
                      route_response ,
                      route_flow ,
                      "}" ;

route_method        = "GET" | "POST" | "PUT" | "PATCH" | "DELETE"
                    | "HEAD" | "OPTIONS" | identifier ;

route_request       = "request" , type_ref ;
route_response      = "response" , type_ref ;
route_flow          = "flow" , identifier ;
```

Routes contain no business logic. They expose an external entry point and
delegate entirely to a named flow.

## Compute Target Blocks

```ebnf
compute_target_block
                    = "compute" , "target" , compute_target_selector ,
                      "{" , { compute_target_clause } , "}" ;

compute_target_selector
                    = "best" | compute_target_name ;

compute_target_clause
                    = "prefer" , "[" , target_list , "]"
                    | "deny" , "[" , deny_list , "]"
                    | "fallback" , compute_target_name ;

target_list         = compute_target_name , { "," , compute_target_name } ;
deny_list           = deny_item , { "," , deny_item } ;

compute_target_name = "cpu" | "gpu" | "npu" | "wasm" | "photonic"
                    | "ai_accelerator" | identifier ;

deny_item           = qualified_name | identifier ;
```

Compute target blocks constrain planning. They must not change security,
governance, authority, effects, validation, redaction, or program meaning.

## Blocks and Statements

```ebnf
block               = "{" , { statement } , "}" ;

statement           = binding_stmt
                    | assignment_stmt
                    | return_stmt
                    | if_stmt
                    | match_stmt
                    | fn_decl
                    | expression_stmt ;

binding_stmt        = binding_prefix , identifier ,
                      [ ":" , type_ref ] , "=" , expression ;

binding_prefix      = "let"
                    | "mut"
                    | "readonly"
                    | "unsafe" , ( "let" | "mut" )
                    | "safe" , "mut" ;

assignment_stmt     = assignable , "=" , expression ;
return_stmt         = "return" , expression ;

if_stmt             = "if" , expression , block , [ "else" , ( block | if_stmt ) ] ;
match_stmt          = match_expr ;
expression_stmt     = expression ;

assignable          = identifier , { "." , identifier | "[" , expression , "]" } ;
```

`unsafe let` marks boundary-origin data. `safe mut` is the controlled upgrade
form after an approved validation/decode gate.

## Expressions and Operators

The expression grammar follows the precedence table in
`docs/Knowledge-Bases/operator-precedence.md`.

```ebnf
expression          = logical_or ;

logical_or          = logical_and , { "||" , logical_and } ;
logical_and         = equality , { "&&" , equality } ;
equality            = comparison , { ( "==" | "!=" ) , comparison } ;
comparison          = additive , { ( "<" | "<=" | ">" | ">=" ) , additive } ;
additive            = multiplicative , { ( "+" | "-" ) , multiplicative } ;
multiplicative      = unary , { ( "*" | "/" | "%" ) , unary } ;
unary               = ( "!" | "-" ) , unary | postfix ;
postfix             = primary , { member_access | call_suffix
                                  | index_suffix | error_propagation } ;

member_access       = "." , identifier ;
call_suffix         = "(" , [ argument_list ] , ")" ;
index_suffix        = "[" , expression , "]" ;
error_propagation   = "?" ;

primary             = literal
                    | identifier
                    | qualified_name
                    | object_literal
                    | list_literal
                    | match_expr
                    | "(" , expression , ")" ;

argument_list       = expression , { "," , expression } ;
qualified_name      = identifier , { "." , identifier } ;

object_literal      = "{" , [ object_field , { "," , object_field } ] ,
                      [ "," ] , "}" ;
object_field        = identifier , ":" , expression ;

list_literal        = "[" , [ expression , { "," , expression } ] ,
                      [ "," ] , "]" ;
```

Operator precedence, tightest last:

| Level | Operators | Associativity |
|---|---|---|
| 10 | `||` | left |
| 20 | `&&` | left |
| 30 | `==` `!=` | left |
| 40 | `<` `<=` `>` `>=` | left |
| 50 | `+` `-` | left |
| 60 | `*` `/` `%` | left |
| 70 | prefix `!` `-` | right |
| 80 | `.` `()` `[]` postfix `?` | left/postfix |

`?` is postfix error propagation. It binds tighter than all infix operators:
`validate.email(raw)? || fallback` parses as `(validate.email(raw)?) || fallback`.

## Governance, Authority, and Policy Blocks

These blocks appear inside `secure flow` bodies and at top-level (governance,
api declarations). They are Phase 7B / 8 semantics; the parser currently
handles them as generic blocks (see `parseGenericBlock` in parser.ts).

```ebnf
governance_decl     = "governance" , identifier , "{" , { governance_clause } , "}" ;

authority_block     = "authority" , authority_action , [ authority_target ] ,
                      "{" , { authority_clause } , "}" ;

authority_action    = "share" | "delegate" | "grant" | identifier ;
authority_target    = qualified_name ;

authority_clause    = "reason" , string_literal
                    | "require" , effect_name
                    | "expires" , string_literal
                    | "audit" , ( "required" | "optional" ) ;

policy_block        = "policy" , "{" , { policy_clause } , "}" ;

policy_clause       = "purpose" , string_literal
                    | "allow" , type_ref , "to" , string_literal
                    | "deny" , type_ref
                    | "require" , effect_name ;

runtime_block       = "runtime" , ( "adaptive" | "deterministic" ) ,
                      [ "{" , { runtime_clause } , "}" ] ;

runtime_clause      = "observe" , identifier
                    | "learn" , "from" , identifier
                    | "optimise" , "[" , identifier_list , "]"
                    | "preserve" , "[" , identifier_list , "]" ;

identifier_list     = identifier , { "," , identifier } ;
```

The `authority` block grants temporary authority for data sharing outside
the normal governed boundary. It must include a `reason` and typically
requires `audit.write` to be declared on the enclosing flow.

The `policy` block constrains what the flow may do with specific data
categories. `purpose` is a machine-readable intent tag the governance
verifier checks against observed behaviour.

The `runtime` block configures the Adaptive Runtime profile for this
flow's execution. `runtime deterministic` disables all adaptive optimisation.

---

## Explicitly Excluded From v1

```text
safe flow, unsafe flow, guard flow
top-level fn
fn effects clauses
assignment expressions
++ / --
ternary ?:
pipeline operator |>
```

